This paper deals with information theoretic concepts such as secrecy capacity and error probability analysis, which are typically studied in the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The paper also deals with the security aspect of communication, which falls under the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category. The use of superposition coding and random code partitioning suggests that the paper may also belong to the Coding Theory and Techniques (cs.CC) sub-category. The paper also deals with the calculation of equivocation, which is a concept studied in the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the use of auxiliary random variables, which is a concept studied in the Signal Processing (cs.SI) sub-category.
